description:
Let’s be Frank - it’s not always sunny when cyber incidents are reported in the news and on social media. Security professionals are increasingly inundated with reporting and notifications concerning cyber threats and the details, or lack thereof, surrounding incidents and trends. Having a process to evaluate collection and sources is key to developing and implementing standards for when to find, integrate, action, corroborate, disregard, and fact-check information coming into your environment. This is especially critical during fast-moving incidents and response activities which necessitate that security professionals consult trusted sources to:
- Obtain facts and accurate explanations concerning threats, TTPs, and incidents;
- Share critical intelligence and identify next steps; and,
- Work through scenarios and solutions to address threats and evolving issues.

We see more cyber incidents reflected in mainstream reporting and social media where narratives can often be misinterpreted, misconstrued, or flat out incorrect - causing security professionals to spend extra time and effort to sort out the facts and ensure accurate information is quickly identified and relayed to stakeholders. In many cases, time is of the essence, resources are limited, and bad information can have serious consequences. We need to be judicious about where we are getting our information from and how we are handling that information, especially if it was relayed to us in a trusted capacity.

From a threat intelligence perspective, we develop expertise for finding sources on a particular set of topics, identifying primary and derivative source materials, detecting circular reporting, corroborating information, and detecting if sources are providing false or misleading information - or disinformation. The confidence we have in our assessments about threats and incidents directly hinges on the quality of our sources, the information provided to us, and unanswered questions and assumptions. Threat intelligence also employs handling frameworks so we can exchange information with a number of internal and external groups. Trust is central to this process, and we need to be selective about which sources we trust as well as be responsible stewards of information entrusted to us.

This presentation will walk through the following to provide attendees with practical guidance and real world examples so they can develop and widen their pool of trusted sources and enhance internal processes for identifying, refining, integrating, analyzing, and sharing information:
- Managing expectations when issues are circulating in the media and online;
- Knowing, trusting, and working with sources, information, and intelligence;
- Identifying new sources to address collection gaps;
- Prioritizing sources based on intelligence requirements;
- Evaluating and validating sources for credibility, accuracy, corroboration, circular reporting, and deception; and,
- Handling information per traffic light protocol (TLP) standards to maintain trusted relationships.

